_data.text:
Empower your NuxtJS application with `@nuxtjs/content` module: write in a `content/` directory and fetch your Markdown, JSON, YAML and CSV files through a MongoDB like API, acting as a **Git-based Headless CMS**.

## Writing content

Learn how to write your `content/`, supporting Markdown, YAML, CSV and JSON: https://content.nuxtjs.org/writing.

## Fetching content

Learn how to fetch your content with `$content`: https://content.nuxtjs.org/fetching.

## Displaying content

Learn how to display your Markdown content with the `<nuxt-content>` component directly in your template: https://content.nuxtjs.org/displaying.

_data.text:
![Cover](/img/articles/cover-action-on-google-introduction.jpg)

Photo by Google Assistant on Google Assistant for Developers


Hi folks, in this article I want to introduce **Action on Google**. A while ago, I had the chance to share this topic in several universities. So I thought, why not write it down here so it can reach more people as well?

At this moment, not many people are familiar with this platform, even though it can reach thousands of devices — including smart speakers, phones, cars, TVs, headphones, and more. Action on Google itself is a platform that lets you build products which extend the functionality of **Google Assistant** and deliver rich conversational experiences. ## What Is Action on Google? With Action on Google, we as developers have the opportunity to:

- create our own custom conversational experiences, - manage conversations with users, - integrate our services into Google Assistant.

Action on Google combines three main technologies:

- machine learning - speech recognition - language understanding

These make it possible to understand what the user says and respond in a natural, conversational way. ## How Does It Work? At a high level, we use the **Conversation API** and the **Actions SDK**.

![Section-2](/img/articles/section-2.jpg)

Photo by Google Assistant on Google Assistant for Developers


- The user says something to Google Assistant. - The Action receives a request that contains the spoken text as a string. - Google handles the **speech recognition** part — converting voice to text. - The text is then parsed and processed so the system can understand the intent. - A response is generated and Google Assistant speaks it back to the user.

The key point here: you don’t have to implement speech recognition or natural language parsing from scratch — Google takes care of that. ## Why Dialogflow? So, what tools can you use to build an Action on Google product?

A great choice is **Dialogflow**.

![Section-3](/img/articles/section-3.jpg)

Photo by Google Assistant on Google Assistant for Developers


Dialogflow is a platform that makes it much easier to build conversational experiences. It lets you create conversational interfaces on top of your products and services by providing a powerful **Natural Language Understanding (NLU)** engine.

In other words, Dialogflow helps you process and understand natural language input, so you can focus more on the logic and experience, not on low-level language processing. ## How Dialogflow Fits In Once the user is talking to your Action, they start with what Google calls a **“user says”** phrase.

![Section-4](/img/articles/section-4.jpg)

Photo by Google Assistant on Google Assistant for Developers


For example:

*“Help me find a recipe for rendang.”*

When the user says this to your Action:

- Google Assistant and Dialogflow process the phrase. - Dialogflow finds the appropriate **intent** to handle it. - The phrase is processed to extract **entities** (important pieces of information). - Dialogflow calls your **webhook** with these entities and the action name. - Your webhook does whatever logic you need (e.g., search recipes) and returns a response. - The response is then spoken back to the user.

Even though the example looks simple, conversational experiences are actually quite hard to implement if you build everything from scratch. Interpreting and processing natural language requires a very robust language parser that understands all the nuances of language.

Dialogflow helps you achieve this more easily by handling NLU for you.
When you use Dialogflow, you create **agents** that can understand varied human language and translate it into structured data that your apps and services can work with. ## Closing That’s a short introduction to **Action on Google**. In the next article, I’ll try my best to share a more concrete demo or hands-on example related to this topic.

**Cheers!**

_data.text:
![Cover](/img/articles/cover-5-ways-adaptability.jpg)

Photo by Mobile Development on Grow with Google


Adaptability is one of the most important skills we can develop today. It shapes how we respond to change, navigate uncertainty, and continue growing in fast-shifting environments.

Joining [Bangkit Academy led by Google, Tokopedia, Gojek, & Traveloka](https://grow.google/intl/id_id/bangkit/?tab=mobile-development) was an exciting journey for me. I had to adapt to a new environment, new people, and a new way of working. Here are the 5 ways I adapted: ## 1. Interacting Adaptability starts with the way we communicate and connect with others. Being adaptable means knowing how to adjust:

- your tone, - your approach, - your expectations, - and your communication style, depending on the person and situation.

Good adaptability makes collaboration smoother and prevents unnecessary conflict. ## 2. Achieving Goals can change. Targets shift. Plans evolve. Adaptable people don’t break when expectations move — they **adjust**.

They:

- redefine what success looks like, - adjust timelines, - remain committed despite obstacles, - and stay flexible enough to change direction when needed.

This helps them stay consistent even when conditions aren’t ideal. ## 3. Learning Adaptability thrives on learning — and not just *any* learning.

It’s about:

- learning new things, - **re-learning** what you thought you knew, - and **un-learning** old habits that no longer work.

Continuous learners adapt faster because they’re open to new perspectives. ## 4. Working The world of work is changing rapidly — remote work, hybrid setups, automation, new tools.

Adaptable people can:

- switch between platforms, - adjust to new workflows, - embrace new responsibilities, - and stay productive in different environments.

This keeps them relevant and resilient. ## 5. Thinking Perhaps the most important form of adaptability:

**mental adaptability**.

This means having a mindset that:

- tolerates uncertainty, - accepts that change is inevitable, - reframes challenges as opportunities, - and stays curious instead of threatened by new things.

Adaptable thinkers don’t just survive change — they grow through it. ## Closing Thoughts Adaptability isn’t a skill you master once. It’s a lifelong practice — a mindset of flexibility, curiosity, and openness.

The more adaptable you become, the more confidently you can navigate the unpredictable world ahead.

**Stay flexible. Stay curious. Keep evolving.**

_data.description: A reflection on how fairness starts long before action — in the way we think, evaluate situations, and internalize our values.
_data.title: Fair from the Mind

children.value: Fairness is more than rules, systems, or policies.
At its core, fairness is a way of
— how we perceive, evaluate, and choose to act.
Before any action happens, thought comes first.
Am I treating others the way I want to be treated?
Am I considering perspectives beyond my own?
Am I aware of the biases I may carry?
When fairness begins in our thinking, fair actions follow naturally.
Our thinking is influenced by many factors — environment, culture, habits.
And sometimes, these influences create challenges:
When we grow used to double standards, fairness becomes blurred.
When we ignore injustice by saying “it’s fine,” we quietly allow it to continue.
When we believe fairness is for others to uphold, not us, we lose our sense of responsibility.
Fair thinking becomes meaningful only when translated into everyday choices:
giving space to voices that are often unheard,
choosing fairness even when it’s inconvenient.
These small actions build integrity over time.
Fairness that grows from within does more than shape individuals — it shapes communities, workplaces, and systems.
Think fairly → act fairly → create change.

_data.text:
![Cover](/img/articles/cover-fair-from-the-mind.jpg)

Photo by Rifqi Ali Ridho on Unsplash


Fairness is more than rules, systems, or policies. At its core, fairness is a way of **thinking** — how we perceive, evaluate, and choose to act. ## Cultivating Fairness Internally Before any action happens, thought comes first.

We ask ourselves:

- Am I treating others the way I want to be treated? - Am I considering perspectives beyond my own? - Am I aware of the biases I may carry?

When fairness begins in our thinking, fair actions follow naturally. ## The Challenge of Thinking Fairly Our thinking is influenced by many factors — environment, culture, habits. And sometimes, these influences create challenges:

- When we grow used to double standards, fairness becomes blurred. - When we ignore injustice by saying “it’s fine,” we quietly allow it to continue. - When we believe fairness is for others to uphold, not us, we lose our sense of responsibility. ## Translating Fairness into Action Fair thinking becomes meaningful only when translated into everyday choices:

- listening actively, not just responding, - correcting ourselves when we misjudge, - giving space to voices that are often unheard, - choosing fairness even when it’s inconvenient.

These small actions build integrity over time. ## Closing Thoughts Fairness that grows from within does more than shape individuals — it shapes communities, workplaces, and systems.

Let’s begin inside ourselves:
Think fairly → act fairly → create change.

**Fairness starts in the mind.**

_data.description: A deep dive into how critical thinking empowers problem-solving in the workplace — by asking better questions, challenging assumptions, and embracing complexity.
_data.title: Critical Thinking & Problem Solving

children.value: In today’s fast-moving environment, solving problems isn’t about having the right answers — it's about asking the right questions.
Critical thinking is the foundation of meaningful problem-solving. It helps us:
and act decisively when uncertainty is high.

Choosing Bangkit was a deliberate decision for me, aiming to enhance my professionalism post-graduation. Facing significant hurdles, particularly from within, has tested my resilience and critical thinking at
Bangkit Academy led by Google, Tokopedia, Gojek, & Traveloka
When you rely purely on intuition or past habits, you limit your possible solutions.
But when you apply critical thinking, you expand them.
You start asking “Why?” instead of accepting “Because”.
You learn to challenge how things have always been done.
You open up for better alternatives.
— Identify exactly what the problem is.
— Collect relevant data, evidence, and perspectives.
— Break down the data, look for patterns, biases, and assumptions.
— Weigh your options, list pros & cons, foresee consequences.
— Choose a path and move, then reflect on results.
When you combine critical thinking with problem-solving, you become more than reactive — you become strategic.
Instead of “fixing what’s broken”, you ask “What needs to change and why?”.
Instead of “emergency mode”, you work in “purpose mode”.
Instead of repeating outcomes, you create new ones.
Great problem-solvers don’t wait for perfect clarity — they act on clear thinking.
They recognise that almost every problem is also an opportunity for growth.
If you’re ready to level-up your thinking, start today: challenge one assumption, ask one better question, and let the process guide you.
Stay curious. Think critically. Solve smart.

_data.text:
![Cover](/img/articles/cover-crticical-thinking-problem-solving.jpg)

Photo by Mobile Development on Grow with Google


In today’s fast-moving environment, solving problems isn’t about having the right answers — it's about asking the right questions. Critical thinking is the foundation of meaningful problem-solving. It helps us:

- break down complex issues, - spot hidden assumptions, - generate better options, - and act decisively when uncertainty is high.

Choosing Bangkit was a deliberate decision for me, aiming to enhance my professionalism post-graduation. Facing significant hurdles, particularly from within, has tested my resilience and critical thinking at [Bangkit Academy led by Google, Tokopedia, Gojek, & Traveloka](https://grow.google/intl/id_id/bangkit/?tab=mobile-development). ## Why Critical Thinking Matters When you rely purely on intuition or past habits, you limit your possible solutions. But when you apply critical thinking, you expand them.

- You start asking “Why?” instead of accepting “Because”. - You learn to challenge how things have always been done. - You open up for better alternatives. ## The Critical Thinking Process - **Clarify** — Identify exactly what the problem is. - **Gather** — Collect relevant data, evidence, and perspectives. - **Analyze** — Break down the data, look for patterns, biases, and assumptions. - **Evaluate** — Weigh your options, list pros & cons, foresee consequences. - **Decide & Act** — Choose a path and move, then reflect on results. ## Problem-Solving in Practice When you combine critical thinking with problem-solving, you become more than reactive — you become strategic.

- Instead of “fixing what’s broken”, you ask “What needs to change and why?”. - Instead of “emergency mode”, you work in “purpose mode”. - Instead of repeating outcomes, you create new ones. ## Closing Thoughts Great problem-solvers don’t wait for perfect clarity — they act on clear thinking. They recognise that almost every problem is also an opportunity for growth.

If you’re ready to level-up your thinking, start today: challenge one assumption, ask one better question, and let the process guide you.

**Stay curious. Think critically. Solve smart.**

toc.text: Empati yang Nyata, Dampak yang Nyata

children.value: Empati bukan hanya soal merasa iba terhadap seseorang.
Lebih dari itu, empati adalah kemampuan
—melihat apa yang mereka lihat, mendengar apa yang mereka dengar, dan merasakan apa yang mereka rasakan.
dan membiarkan diri kita berubah oleh apa yang kita pelajari.
Menjadi orang lain—bukan dalam arti kehilangan jati diri—tetapi memahami mereka secara utuh.
Empati yang Nyata, Dampak yang Nyata
Ketika kita mendesain dengan empati, kita tidak hanya membuat produk—kita menciptakan pengalaman manusia.
Empati tidak menuntut kita menjadi orang lain selamanya—empati mengundang kita meminjam lensa mereka sesaat, agar kita pulang dengan pemahaman yang lebih luas dan tujuan yang lebih kuat.
Pilihlah empati, bukan hanya sebagai nilai, tetapi sebagai cara bekerja, peduli, dan berkarya.
Karena untuk benar-benar melayani orang lain—kita harus mampu melihat mereka terlebih dahulu.

_data.text:
![Cover](/img/articles/cover-empati-adalah-kemampuan-menjadi-orang-lain.jpg)

Photo by Martin Tampubolon on Unsplash


Empati bukan hanya soal merasa iba terhadap seseorang. Lebih dari itu, empati adalah kemampuan **masuk ke dunia orang lain**—melihat apa yang mereka lihat, mendengar apa yang mereka dengar, dan merasakan apa yang mereka rasakan. ## Masuk ke Dunia Orang Lain Ketika kita benar-benar berempati, kita:

- menunda asumsi kita sendiri, - mendengarkan sepenuh hati, - dan membiarkan diri kita berubah oleh apa yang kita pelajari.

Menjadi orang lain—bukan dalam arti kehilangan jati diri—tetapi memahami mereka secara utuh. ### Empati yang Nyata, Dampak yang Nyata Empati mengubah:

- prototipe menjadi pengalaman bermakna, - data riset menjadi cerita manusia, - fitur menjadi momen koneksi.

Ketika kita mendesain dengan empati, kita tidak hanya membuat produk—kita menciptakan pengalaman manusia. ## Refleksi Penutup Empati tidak menuntut kita menjadi orang lain selamanya—empati mengundang kita meminjam lensa mereka sesaat, agar kita pulang dengan pemahaman yang lebih luas dan tujuan yang lebih kuat.

Pilihlah empati, bukan hanya sebagai nilai, tetapi sebagai cara bekerja, peduli, dan berkarya.

**Karena untuk benar-benar melayani orang lain—kita harus mampu melihat mereka terlebih dahulu.**

_data.description: Behind every milestone, there are countless unseen nights of doubt, experimentation, and persistence. This is a reflection on learning to trust the slow, quiet moments that shape who we become.
_data.title: Quiet Growth: Learning to Trust the Process

children.value: Behind every accomplishment lies a version of ourselves that most people never meet:
the moments we consider giving up.
But these “unseen” elements matter. They shape our endurance, deepen our understanding, and slowly build the resilience needed to do meaningful work.
No trophy or recognition can fully represent this journey — and maybe that’s the point.
Some seasons of life feel stagnant — as if nothing meaningful is happening.
But often, these slow seasons are the ones forming our foundation.
Just like how a tree grows its roots deeper before reaching upward, we too grow inward before we grow outward.
Learning to trust the process means:
allowing ourselves to grow at our own pace,
appreciating the progress that isn’t visible yet.
There is no universal timeline for success, creativity, or fulfillment.
What takes months for one person may take years for another — and that’s okay.
What matters is not how fast we move, but whether we keep moving.
Real growth isn’t a race. It’s a personal journey.
If you’re in a season that feels slow, uncertain, or unremarkable — don’t be discouraged. You’re building something beneath the surface that will carry you through the chapters ahead.
Keep going. Trust the process. The results will come in their own time.

_data.text:
![Cover](/img/articles/cover-quiet-growth.jpg)

Photo by Tom Allport on Unsplash


## The Parts No One Sees Behind every accomplishment lies a version of ourselves that most people never meet:

- the late-night doubts, - the abandoned drafts, - the trial-error cycles, - the moments we consider giving up.
But these “unseen” elements matter. They shape our endurance, deepen our understanding, and slowly build the resilience needed to do meaningful work. No trophy or recognition can fully represent this journey — and maybe that’s the point. ## Trusting the Slow Pace Some seasons of life feel stagnant — as if nothing meaningful is happening. But often, these slow seasons are the ones forming our foundation.

Just like how a tree grows its roots deeper before reaching upward, we too grow inward before we grow outward. Learning to trust the process means:

- allowing ourselves to grow at our own pace, - understanding that consistency beats intensity, - appreciating the progress that isn’t visible yet. ## Progress Looks Different for Everyone There is no universal timeline for success, creativity, or fulfillment.
What takes months for one person may take years for another — and that’s okay.
What matters is not how fast we move, but whether we keep moving.
Real growth isn’t a race. It’s a personal journey.
## Closing Thoughts Quiet growth is still growth.
The small steps still count.
The invisible progress still matters.

If you’re in a season that feels slow, uncertain, or unremarkable — don’t be discouraged. You’re building something beneath the surface that will carry you through the chapters ahead.

**Keep going. Trust the process. The results will come in their own time.**

_data.text:
![Cover](/img/articles/cover-kita-akan-mudah-tergantikan.jpg)

Photo by Giulia Sanfelici on Unsplash


Suka atau tidak, kenyataannya banyak dari kita bisa tergantikan. Dalam dunia yang bergerak cepat ini, kemampuan kita — sekuat apa pun — bisa dengan mudah digantikan oleh sesuatu atau seseorang yang lain. ## Kenapa Kita Mudah Tergantikan? Karena:

- Ada banyak orang yang belajar hal yang sama, - Teknologi membuat banyak pekerjaan menjadi otomatis, - Persaingan tidak lagi sebatas orang vs orang, tapi manusia vs sistem, manusia vs algoritma, manusia vs jaringan global.

Dengan menyadari ini, kita tidak jadi merasa kecil—sebaliknya, kita mendapatkan **dorongan untuk tumbuh**. ## Apa Yang Bisa Kita Lakukan? Jika kita tahu bahwa kita mudah tergantikan, maka kita bisa memilih untuk:

- Fokus pada **keahlian unik** yang hanya bisa dilakukan manusia — nilai, kreativitas, empati. - Terus belajar dan beradaptasi — karena menggantikan diri sendiri yang statis lebih baik daripada menunggu digantikan orang lain. - Menciptakan **nilai tambah** bukan hanya output — berbeda bukan hanya karena siapa kita, tapi karena bagaimana kita bekerja dan apa yang kita hasilkan. ## Penutup Mudah digantikan tidak harus jadi kelemahan — itu bisa jadi pengingat bahwa kita harus terus **berevolusi**.
Biarkan kesadaran ini mendorong kita untuk menjadi versi kita yang lebih matang, bukan versi kita yang takut digantikan.

**Karena kita mungkin bisa tergantikan—tapi kita bisa memilih untuk menjadi tak tergantikan dalam cara kita berpikir, bekerja, dan memberi makna.**

_data.description: The variety of sports favored by the people has become a new business opportunity to rent out sports facilities such as soccer, badminton, basketball, and others. Although the sports facility rental business has been growing for years, the sports facility rental system still uses a conventional system, namely contacting the owner or manager of sports facilities via telephone, SMS, or chat via the WhatsApp application.
_data.title: Fitz
_data.subtitle: A Rental Sports Fields App

toc.text: What I learned from Designing for Fitz

children.value: Convenient to Renting Sports Fields with FITZ

For years, the sports facility rental system has been using a conventional system, namely contacting the owner or manager of sports facilities via telephone, SMS, or WhatsApp. We had an idea to create FITZ — a rental sports field app. Through FITZ, users can rent and see information about sports fields in their closest area or even far away from their reach. We believe that FITZ can bring a much better user experience for users to rent sports fields.

In order to identify the user flows through the app and areas where the navigational flow can be improved, we created a user flow. The flowchart begins with the consumer’s entry point on the product, like an onboarding screen or homepage, and ends with the final action or outcome. In FITZ, the final action consists of a successful transfer, indicating that the user has been successfully transferred through payment for booking the sports field.

Creating low-fidelity wireframes in UI/UX Design is an essential step involving visualizing digital applications’ skeleton. UX Wireframe provides a blueprint of the page structure, layout, information, and functions. The result of the discussion in Crazy 8s led me to create UX Wireframe to keep the concept user-focused.

Based on the research by Herman Cerrato entitled “The Meaning of Colors,” green symbolizes growth and harmony. A calming color also that’s very pleasing to the senses. As a sports app, FITZ uses the color green to represent health and healing.

Rubik is a sans serif font family with slightly rounded corners designed by Philipp Hubert and Sebastian Fischer at Hubert & Fischer as part of the Chrome Cube Lab project. Rubik is a 5-weight family with Roman and Italic styles that accompanies Rubik Mono One, a monospaced variation of the Black roman design.

After we decided on the color palette, typography, icons, and name of the application, the high-fidelity design is created. The high-fidelity design includes actual content, typefaces, colors, image dimensions, and branding elements.
What I learned from Designing for Fitz

Research is important to validate our assumptions and how confirm what the users need. Collaborating provides a space to be able to exchange ideas and discuss possibilities that can and cannot be applied. Usability testing is a very crucial step of this project. We can see the pain points felt by the user, then find out which flow is not good and which flow can be maintained.

_data.title: Juragan Material
_data.subtitle: Unveiling The New Interface

toc.text: What I learned from Designing for Juragan Material

children.value: Unveiling The New Interface: Juragan Material’s Homepage Redesign

Juragan Material is an Indonesian B2B e-commerce platform specializing in building materials. We aim to revolutionize the construction industry through digital transformation. This case study details our UI/UX redesign process to enhance user experience and align with the new logo launch on Apr 3, 2023. The goal is to create an engaging, intuitive, and visually captivating homepage that reflects their commitment to excellence.

Juragan Material planned to launch a new logo on Apr 3, 2023. To align with the new branding, adjustments are required for the user interface (UI) on the homepage, header, and footer. The primary goal is to enhance the user experience (UX) by addressing existing issues and making the homepage more engaging and visually appealing.

We identified critical issues with Juragan's previous homepage, including low engagement and clickability awareness. To address these challenges, we embarked on a comprehensive redesign, focusing on improving the visual hierarchy and optimizing white space usage. Our user-centric approach aims to create a captivating and seamless user experience, drawing visitors deeper into Juragan's platform

We revamped Juragan Material's homepage by restructuring its information architecture for a more streamlined user experience and optimized white space. The new design combines "Register as Business" and "Register as Vendor" into one section.

In the context of Juragan Material's homepage redesign, typography plays a crucial role in conveying a sense of professionalism and clarity to the user experience. While the logo font is Poppins, the decision to use the Inter font for the website's content was deliberate.

The font's legibility ensures that vital information is easily accessible to users, fostering a seamless browsing experience. By opting for Inter, Juragan Material ensures a consistent and visually appealing presentation that aligns with their industry expertise and trustworthy reputation.

The top banner, being a crucial element of the homepage, required a redesign that captured the attention of users and conveyed Juragan's value proposition effectively. The team collaborated to create a visually compelling banner that featured striking imagery and clear, concise messaging. A balance between aesthetics and information hierarchy was maintained to avoid overwhelming the users.
What I learned from Designing for Juragan Material

This case study's main limitation is the absence of formal research and analysis. Without user research, the design decisions may not fully meet Juragan Material's audience needs. The redesign lacks data-driven insights but serves as an exercise in exploring design improvements. The case study has tight deadlines, limiting in-depth design exploration and iterations. The pressure to deliver quickly may impact thoroughness and testing.
